<Callout type="warning" title="VFD current measurement with average-responding meters">
  A variable frequency drive (inverter) draws current from the mains with a highly peaked, non-sinusoidal waveform — crest factors of 3 to 5 are common. An average-responding clamp meter or multimeter will read the input current of a VFD as 30–60% lower than the true RMS current. This causes seriously undersized cable and fuse selection. Always use a True RMS instrument for measurements on VFD-fed or inverter systems.
</Callout>

<p>The practical situations where True RMS measurement is essential include: current measurement on VFD/inverter inputs; voltage measurement on UPS output (often a modified sine wave); power quality analysis; harmonic current measurement; current measurement in data centres and commercial buildings with large switched-mode power supply loads; and any measurement where you need to verify whether a protection device (fuse, MCB) is correctly rated.</p>

